Date: 4 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada 4 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/english/protection/warnings/sars/numbers.html>

Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) 4 Apr 2003 4:00 PM ET
Latest Canadian Numbers on SARS
---------------------------------
As of 4 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of approximately 187
probable or suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in
Canada. There have been 7 deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting. The information
contained in this update is based on the best available information Health
Canada has at this time.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario is reporting 71 probable and 78 suspect cases. All cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 3 probable and 23 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.
These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM ET 4 Apr 2003. For specific
information on the provincial numbers, please contact the appropriate
provincial health department.
[This represents a total of 74 probable cases and 113 suspected cases, an
increase of 5 probable and 4 suspected cases from 3 Apr 2003. - Mod.MPP]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Newswire reports continue to mention numbers of suspected cases
elsewhere. With the exception of the USA, all other countries are
reporting only probable cases of SARS to WHO; and even among these reports
we have seen probable cases eliminated as other etiologies are confirmed to
explain the clinical syndromes. For this reason we have been avoiding
posting these newswires. A good example of such was a report today on All
Africa of a "suspected case" in an individual transferred to a hospital in
South Africa from Maputo, Mozambique, with a history of recent travel to
Hong Kong. The newswire also goes on to say that it may be malaria, but is
being treated as a suspected case until test results were known.
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200304010749.html>
Again, until a definitive etiologic agent is identified, thus making
laboratory confirmation possible, there will continue to be discrepancies
in "case count" numbers and reports.
Today's reports reflect the beginning of daily reporting from China, which
will allow for a closer following of the outbreak. For those readers who
are going directly to this comment, the daily summary (from WHO [1][C]
above) is: "As of today and including the new data from China, a cumulative
total of 2353 SARS cases and 84 deaths have been reported from 16
countries. This represents an increase of 83 cases and 5 deaths compared
with yesterday. The deaths occurred in Canada (1), China (3), and Singapore
(1). New cases were reported in Canada (7), China (30), Hong Kong SAR
(27), Taiwan, China (1), Singapore (2), and the United States of America
(15)."
The discussion on the investigation into possible sewage line break in the
Amoy Gardens is interesting. In an earlier update it was postulated that a
sewage backflow with formation of airborne fomites would explain the rapid
expansion in the numbers of cases reported from a single block of flats in
Hong Kong. We look forward to seeing the technical details of this
evaluation. - Mod.MPP]
